See Also
Dysentery, simultaneous dog & human: RFI 980520075923
[1
Date: Wed, 20 May 1998 09:15:34 -0500
From: Dr. Norman Ronald <n-ronald@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>

The Associate Knowledge Base for Infectious and Parasitic Diseases of Man
list the following diseases as a cause of dysentery in both man and dogs:
Anthrax
Campylobacterial enteritis
Enterocolic yersiniosis
Salmonellosis
Zygomycosis
Amoebosis (here man is the reservoir)
Balantidiosis
Heterophyetosis
Schistosomiasis
--
N.C. Ronald Ph.D.
TVMDL TAMU
College Station Tx.
e-mail: n-ronald@tamu.edu
[2
Date: Wed, 20 May 1998 09:03:47 -0400
From: Patrick McDonough <plm2@cornell.edu>

_Campylobacter_ in dogs it seems likely to be the culprit in this reported
episode. We hardly ever see _Salmonella_ in healthy adult dogs (salmonellosis
is more common in pups and pregnant bitches) that we have occassion to do a
diagnostic work up on.
References:
BOOSINGER TR, DILLON AR. _Campylobacter jejuni_ infection in dogs and the
effect of erythromycin and tetracycline therapy on fecal shedding. JAAHA
1992; 28:33-38
WILLIAMS LP. Campylobacteriosis. JAVMA 1988;193:52-53
--
